article.headline: Ilgauskas' 19 lead Cavs
article.story:
CLEVELAND -- The Cavaliers finally put it all together with their rookie leading the way. No, not THAT rookie. Jason Kapono, the Cavaliers' less-hyped first-year player, scored 16 points and Darius Miles added 15 as Cleveland snapped an eight-game losing streak with a 95-85 win over the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday night. "I just tried to come off the bench and play solid," said Kapono, who went 6-of-8 from the field and made two 3-pointers in 22 minutes. "That's my role." Zydrunas Ilgauskas added 19 points and eight rebounds for the Cavs, whose reserves outscored Atlanta's 44-10 and led them to just their fifth win -- and first since beating the Los Angeles Clippers on Nov. 18. "Everybody was clicking at the same time," said Cavs forward Carlos Boozer. "The bench gave us a great game." The Cavs withstood a season-high, 43-point effort from Atlanta's Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who went 17-of-27 and added 12 rebounds. "We couldn't stop him," Cavs coach Paul Silas said. "We did everything we could think of." Jason Terry had 14 points for Atlanta, which has dropped four straight and six of seven. LeBron James had only eight points, six rebounds and five assists. But Cleveland's rookie star made a big steal late in the game, picking Abdur-Rahim clean and hitting a layup with 2:57 left to help the Cavs, who had recently blown several games in the fourth quarter, hang on. "We've been in so many games down the stretch that tonight we finally came together and got it done," James said. "We knew we had been here before and said, 'Let's close this out and get a win."' The Cavs got a huge lift from their second unit. Chris Mihm had six points and eight rebounds, and Kevin Ollie chipped in with six points, four rebounds and three assists in 19 minutes while running the point with James on the bench. "Coach said before the game, we need a big play from everybody," James said. "Tonight, everybody picked it up." After Abdur-Rahim scored four quick points to open the fourth, Kapono, the Cavs' second-round pick, countered with two free throws and a jumper to give Cleveland a 75-70 lead. Dion Glover's layup closed the gap for Atlanta, but Boozer was finally able to slow Abdur-Rahim, and Mihm made a pair of free throws before banking in a five-footer in the lane to put Cleveland ahead 79-72. Abdur-Rahim then went more then five minutes without scoring before making two free throws to pull the Hawks to 86-80. However, Miles made three free throws, James made his steal and layin and Kapono drained a jumper to cap a 7-0 spurt that gave Cleveland a 93-80 lead with 1:48 remaining. Abdur-Rahim didn't care how may points he scored. "I'd trade all of them. Sincerely, I mean that," he said. "This is a bad loss for us, there's no other way to put it." Kapono scored 10 points, hitting a 3-pointer with 5.1 seconds left in the second quarter as the Cavs overcame a seven-point deficit and took a 44-42 halftime lead. "I'm going to shoot my way in, and I'm going to shoot my way out," Kapono said. James knows that when he gets his fellow rookie the ball, it's probably going to wind up in the basket. "Certain guys you want to shoot when they get the ball," James said. "Even he's got just a little space, I'm looking for him." Ricky Davis had 12 points in 19 minutes -- just four in the first half before he was benched by Silas. After Davis forced a shot and committed a turnover, Silas sat him for the final 4:09 of the first quarter. Davis, who was visibly upset at being pulled, didn't play in the second period.

Game notes
Hawks F Stephen Jackson received four stitches after getting cut in the first quarter. He returned and finished with four points. ... The Cavs are 4-0 at home vs. Eastern Conference teams. ... Cleveland, winless in 12 road games this season and losers of 33 straight away from Gund Arena, plays its next three at home before going to Indiana on Dec. 15. ... Atlanta had won six in a row over Cleveland and 25 of the previous 32 meetings.
